snippet.textDisplay:
I am SO grateful for this video. One of my children (almost fifteen years old) has Dissociative Identity Disorder. We found out about it last year, and it threw all of us into so many questions. A vast majority of people with DID get it because of trauma and abuse within the home, but my child, I'm told, is unusual because there was no trauma and abuse in the home. Their trauma happened outside of the home, and no one, not even my child, knew about it because the alters showed up to protect and hide that trauma. Finding out that there even had been trauma was devastating. Finding out that there were alters was confusing at first but NOT devastating--they are all amazing and wonderful and we love them all. We, as a family, have been doing absolutely everything we can to love and support all of them (there are seven people in their system--two littles, four teens, and a twenty-three-year-old). They are all extremely open about it now, and they go places and interact with friends and family openly as themselves, so I've been trying to spread awareness and knowledge, and I've been advocating like crazy so that people will treat all seven of my children with kindness and respect. (They all see themselves as my children, and I see them the same way, and I get called Mom, Mommy, or Mother depending on which one is fronting.) I even started a blog using pseudonyms so I could talk about some experiences--with all of their permission, of course. I don't use their real names, or mine, because as much as I want to advocate for them, I also want to protect them.

Anthony, you impressed me so much with how you handled these interviews and with the absolute respect you showed to each alter. I am so thankful I can share this video to help spread awareness of what DID actually is.

snippet.textDisplay: As someone who dated someone with DID I really hated seeing Split come out. I never watched it because I didn't want to support a movie that could fuel such a negative stigma on the disorder. My ex had a few alters and I don't really remember some of their names. We didn't talk about them much because it would trigger them. I know he had 3 that came out the most, one was I don't want to say was him but like his default alter ? That's the most I could describe it. He had one that was super annoying (and he knew it). Very loud and obnoxious, enjoyed walking around like a weirdo. The other I remember was a very angry and more "evil" alter, he didn't come out very often and was the one my ex would hold back the most. (Not ganna lie, that one was the best in bed tho lmfaooo). He was made self aware of his disorder when his art teacher showed him one of his paintings and was telling him how good it was just for him to be like "I didn't make that" and was soon diagnosed. He is an incredible artist but it didn't work out between us as I lost feelings and other reasons.

snippet.textDisplay: Hi Anthony if you’re reading this although I’m not too sure anyone will, I’m Adrienne and I was really hoping that you might be able to make a video about borderline personality disorder (aka BPD), I think it’s really important to educate people on it because it’s a really hard thing to deal with especially when a lot of people commonly get it confused with bipolar disorder and DID. I hope that more people would understand the effects that it has on day to day life and become more aware of it. I think it’s hard because a lot of people don’t actually know about it or know what it is or if they have it. Please keep an open mind to the idea and if needed you can contact me (big stretch I know) but I think it’d be an amazing thing to have someone so popular and well respected in the community to talk about something like this. This video has really educated me and given me a better perspective and understanding of people with DID and for that I’m very grateful. I have loved your work since I was very small and I feel like as I grew as a person you’ve grown with me and I’ll always cherish that. Thank you for just being yourself, we all love you.

snippet.textDisplay: We're here to learn about ourself as a person and/or a body. Me and my friend are trying to get our parents to understand about stuff like this. We're trying to get our parents to let us get tested for BPD. It can be hard to cope and hard to get our parents to understand. We really don't want to tell our parents but we know it's best for us. Recently we've been more in a constant state of co-consciousness and it's hard to deal with so many people (there are only 5, including a little but still) basically yelling at me and trying to get me (the host) to do what they want me to do. I have a really hard time doing certain things and in some cases it can be hard for me to talk. I've taken to writing down my thoughts but that can also be hard to do. Again with everyone adding input and co-existing. And them talking about this is making me cry because i dont feel like i can come forward with this

snippet.textDisplay: I LOVE this video Anthony.  For me this is definitely the best one of these video's that you have ever done, it is VERY good and insightful into the world of DID.  Prior to this video, I didn't know that this disorder and with how it effects the brains of these people, that it is quite literally multiple people living within the same body.  I also learned that they are as likely as anybody else to do things that could hurt other people, if not it's more likely for them to be less likely than anybody without DID to do something that would harm somebody else.  Finally, the fact that more people have DID that schizophrenia is something I would've NEVER known, that's absolutely insane to think about.
